  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Extradition treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated legal actions against financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- National laws must align with international standards\n- Banks and financial institutions required to implement AML protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing\n- Criminal prosecution across jurisdictions\n- Coordinated financial intelligence gathering\n\n5. Compliance Frameworks\n- Risk assessment protocols\n- Due diligence requirements\n- Uniform reporting standards\n- Consistent legal definitions of money laundering\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating financial crime globally, balancing national sovereignty with international cooperation.",
